1_Q18: Mt. Adams Institute's Cascade Mountain School
1_Q29: All of our educators are trained on our emergency action plan and have at least first aid and CPR training. At the beginning of each program all staff and chaperones from the visiting school will meet with our program coordinator where we will give them our emergency action plan and go over the steps: 1. Assess the situation, 2. If the situation is a life threatening emergency, contact Emergency Response (911) immediately, etc. On the back of this plan there is a list of Mt. Adams Institute staff to contact, which is updated before each program, based on staff availability. Staff and chaperones are instructed to call down this list in the order given (if it is a non-life threatening emergency, or emergency response has already been notified) until a member of staff has been reached. The Trout Lake Volunteer Fire Department is within a 5 minute response time.
1_Q31: Paved road,Gravel/dirt road,Extra large vehicle (Such semi-tuck with trailer, standard bus, class A RV),Large vehicles (such as semi without trailer, short bus length, Class C RV, truck with trailer),Standard vehicle (Such as truck without trailer, SUV, sedan),Small vehicle (Such as motorcycle, hybrid, smart car)
1_Q33: We are located at the edge of the Gifford Pinchot National Forest, where we enjoy access to rivers, lakes, streams, forest, old growth forest, lava tubes, and more. We take students into the Gifford Pinchot National Forest to explore the geology of volcanoes, lakes, wildfire ecology, and wildlife unique to the Cascade Mountain Range. Our location in Trout Lake allows students to explore many different kind of land and land use, like agricultural farmland that exists in a valley created by a lahar from Mt. Adams.

1_Q39: Capacity of 60. Our Forest Campus is a 5-acre rustic camp facility in the Gifford Pinchot National Forest right behind the Mt. Adams Ranger District Office in Trout Lake, WA.  The beautiful Forest Campus includes three bunkhouses, a study hall, a mess hall, open fields, woods, and nature trails.  The facility has beds to sleep 60, on twin size beds and cots. The bunkhouses are single-sex buildings and include bathrooms and showers. Each room, which is shared by two-three people, has two beds, a small amount of storage space, and room for a tri-fold mat (third person). The rooms are clean, basic, and comfortable.
1_Q40: Capacity of 60. Our Forest Campus is a 5-acre rustic camp facility. There is ample space for schools to tent camp in our fields. Schools would bring there own tents and share 2-3 people to a tent. Groups have access to the bathrooms and showers in our bunkhouses. We also take groups backpacking and camping in the Gifford Pinchot National Forest. These trips are for groups of up to 12. Schools often send groups in smaller pod or advisory groups to have immersive nature experiences.
1_Q41: We can accommodate students of limited mobility in our dining area (including a bathroom). The dining area is accessible by ramp.
1_Q42: Bunkhouse access for participants of limited mobility. More covered outdoor space.
1_Q43: We are submitting a grant this winter that we hope will help us fund updates on our facilities, to be completed before the Spring Outdoor School season. Some of our projects will include creating more covered outdoor space and creating more accessible spaces for limited mobility participants.
1_Q53: Our facility was built 1976. Renovations are on going, last year all of our buildings got new windows and this year we have installed new toilets and new floors. We are currently assessing our facility for ADA upgrades and improvements.

1_Q38_1_TEXT: 1 classroom - 50 students, 1 lab space - 15 students, and our dining hall can be used as an alternate meeting space
1_Q39:
We have the following layout, by cabin: 

Lodge- Twin beds. Sleeps 18 in three bedrooms. One room with 6 beds, one with 8 and one with 4 beds. 

Bunkhouse- Twin beds. One large room with 20. 

Cabin 4- 13 beds. Downstairs has two rooms, each with 4 twin beds (bunk beds) for a total of 8 twin beds downstairs. Upstairs has one room with 1 queen and 2 twins, and a second room with 1 queen and 1 full.

Cabin 5- 14 beds. This cabin is virtually identical to Cabin 4, with the same bed configuration downstairs. Upstairs has one room with 1 queen and 2 twins, and a second room with 2 queens and 1 twin.

Cabin 7- 8 beds. Upstairs has 6 twins. There are two private rooms downstairs. One has a full and the other a queen size bed, best for adults.
1_Q41: Yes, cabins 4 and 5 are ADA accessible and have sleeping spaces on the first floor.
1_Q42: We have limited sleeping, dining, and indoor classroom capacity, currently serving a maximum of 60 students and 15 chaperones.
1_Q53: Jawbone Flats was first built as a mining town in 1929. Certain buildings have been renovated over the years - our main lodge was rebuilt in the 1970s, cabins 4 and 5 were rebuilt in 2000, and the indoor classroom rebuilt in the early 2000s.
